1. Environment & Bootstrapping: Escaping the BIOS
        We use the Limine bootloader (modern open-source bootloader designed mainly for hobby OS development) to handle the ugly firmware initialization.
        Limine forces the CPU into 64-bit Long Mode, establishes a flat stack, and jumps directly into our C entry point (`kernel_main`).

• Limine is a modern open-source bootloader designed mainly for hobby OS development, kernel experimentation, and modern low-level systems work.

-> What a Bootloader Actually Does:
    When you press the power button:

    1. CPU resets
    2. Firmware starts:
    •   BIOS (old)
    •   UEFI (modern)
    3. Firmware loads a bootloader
    4. Bootloader loads the kernel into memory
    5. Bootloader prepares hardware/environment
    6. Control jumps to kernel entry point

   bootloader is basically, The bridge between firmware and operating system.

   Limine is native 64 bit booting and also less complexity and it handles all on its own.
   older systems were crap, 32 bit focus, messy transitions, legacy constraints.

-> Limine Boot Flow:
                Power On
                   ↓
            BIOS/UEFI firmware
                   ↓
         Limine bootloader loaded
                   ↓
     Limine reads config + filesystem
                   ↓
        Limine loads kernel ELF
                   ↓
       Limine sets up environment
                   ↓
    Paging / framebuffer / memory map
                   ↓
       Jump to kernel entry point

• The kernel is usually compiled as an: Executable and Linkable Format executable.

•Limine:
   1. parses ELF headers
   2. loads sections into correct memory locations
   3. handles relocations if needed
   4. maps segments properly
   5. jumps to kernel entry point

