• Real production OSes dont use Limine, they have their custom bootloaders. So later we'll make ur own but for now we are gonna use Limine to reduce the pain.

-> What does "Limine forces the CPU into 64-bit Long Mode” actually mean?
•Limine performs all the painful low-level CPU setup required to switch the processor from the firmware’s startup state into modern 64-bit execution mode before your kernel begins.
•When an x86 computer powers on, the CPU starts in a very ancient compatibility state inherited from the 1970s/80s:
       CPU reset
           ↓
     16-bit Real Mode

• Real mode has:
        16-bit registers
        1 MB memory limit
        segmented memory
        no paging
        no memory protection
        no privilege separation

Basically DOS-era execution, We CANNOT run a modern kernel properly there.

•Modern x86_64 kernels run in:
    64-bit Long Mode
    This enables:
            64-bit registers
            64-bit addressing
            paging
            virtual memory
            modern instruction set
            higher-half kernels
            large memory support
    Without long mode, we don have 16 bit environment.

• Limine performs the ugly transition chain:
       Real Mode
           ↓
      Protected Mode
           ↓
      Paging Setup
           ↓
       PAE Enable
           ↓
    Long Mode Enable
           ↓
   64-bit Kernel Entry

This involves manipulating:
    control registers
    page tables
    GDT
    MSRs
    paging flags

-> To enter Long Mode manually, we must:
    1. Build a GDT (Global Descriptor Table):
    defines memory segments and privilege setup.
    Even though segmentation is mostly disabled in 64-bit mode, you STILL need a valid GDT to enter Long Mode.

    2. Enable Protected Mode:
    CPU starts in Real Mode.
    must set: CR0.PE

    to enter:
        Protected Mode
    This enables:
        32-bit execution
        protected memory model

    3. Enable PAE:
    must enable:
        Physical Address Extension
    by setting:
        CR4.PAE
    Long Mode REQUIRES PAE paging structures.

    4. Create Page Tables:
    64-bit mode REQUIRES paging.
    must create:
        PML4
        PDPT
        PD
        PT
     "hierarchy."
    Modern x86_64 memory translation depends entirely on this.

    5. Enable Long Mode Bit:
    You must write to a special MSR:
        IA32_EFER
    and set:
        LME = Long Mode Enable
    using instructions like:
        rdmsr
        wrmsr

    6. Enable Paging
    Set:
        CR0.PG
    Now paging activates.
    At THIS point:
       the CPU is technically ready for Long Mode.

    7. Far Jump Into 64-bit Code Segment
    Finally:
    you must perform a special jump to reload CS:
        jmp 64bit_code_segment:start64
    Only NOW does the CPU begin executing:
        actual 64-bit instructions.

