-> What Actually Happens on Boot
   When an x86 CPU resets:

      CPU Reset
          ↓
      Real Mode
          ↓
   Firmware executes
          ↓
  Bootloader executes
          ↓
Switch to Protected Mode
          ↓
  Switch to Long Mode
          ↓
    Kernel starts

• Even on a modern CPUs, the reset state is still basically legacy x86 startup behavior.
• X86 still do this because of "Backward Compatibility", "Old software should still boot"

-> Protected Mode vs Long Mode:
    Protected Mode (32-bit)(by Intel):
    Adds:
       • memory protection
       • privilege rings
       • multitasking support
       • 32-bit addressing

    Long Mode (64-bit)(by AMD):
    Adds:
    • 64-bit registers
    • modern paging
    • large virtual memory
    • cleaner execution model

-> You CANNOT Jump Directly From Real Mode to Long Mode:
•You must pass through intermediate setup stages:
    Protected Mode
    paging setup
    PAE
    MSR configuration
before Long Mode activates.

-> BIOS vs UEFI:
    BIOS Path:
        Real Mode
           ↓
          BIOS
           ↓
       Bootloader
           ↓
     Protected Mode
           ↓
       Long Mode

   UEFI Path:
           Real Mode
              ↓
         UEFI firmware
              ↓
 UEFI internally sets modern state
              ↓
          Bootloader
              ↓
            Kernel

• UEFI often already executes in:
    32-bit
    or
    64-bit mode
which simplifies bootloader work.

-> The CPU has multiple cores, and each core can execute independently but on boot only ONE core starts automatically. This is called BSP (Bootstrap Processor),
the other cores are inactive/asleep called as AP (Application Processors).
Then later the kernel wakes all and assigns the cores with processes.
the kernel must:
    detect AP cores
    initialize them
    give them stacks
    switch them into Long Mode
    synchronize startup
This process is: SMP initialization
